                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d521">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.4131/150: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Atherton</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-03-19T13:00:00+00:00"
                            >March 19, 1936—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received March 19—11 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>136. Department’s 84, March 18, 1 p.m. As indicated in my 79, February 26, 7
                    p.m., although Eden read and made extensive notes from the memorandum, I did not
                    leave a copy with him as a precaution against the question at issue passing into
                    a wholly technical sphere of discussion. The ensuing political crisis has
                    prevented a personal consideration of the question by the relevant members of
                    the Cabinet and has in fact changed the whole tactical situation. In the
                    circumstances I venture to suggest that a copy of the memorandum be given to the
                    British Ambassador at Washington since these [this?] would afford an opportunity
                    for impressing upon him again the American viewpoint.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Atherton</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
